content.text:
Here’s what was going on: the strip under your tab bar isn’t your layout “ending early” — it’s the **Android system navigation bar**, which was still using the default **black** background. Your app already respects safe area; the system chrome just didn’t match `COLORS.bg`.

### What we did

1. **`expo-navigation-bar`** (already installed) — On Android we now set:
   - **Navigation bar background** → `#242C3B` (same as `COLORS.bg`)
   - **Top border** of that bar → same color so there’s no hard line
   - **Button style** → `light` so the gesture pill / buttons stay visible on the dark bar  

2. **`app.json` config plugin** — So **release / `expo run:android` builds** pick up the same nav bar styling from native config, not only from JS at runtime.

```34:48:c:\Users\debob\Desktop\GymBros TakeHome\app\_layout.tsx
  useEffect(() => {
    void SystemUI.setBackgroundColorAsync(COLORS.bg);
    if (Platform.OS !== 'android') return;
    void (async () => {
      try {
        await NavigationBar.setBackgroundColorAsync(COLORS.bg);
        await NavigationBar.setBorderColorAsync(COLORS.bg);
        await NavigationBar.setButtonStyleAsync('light');
      } catch {
        /* Expo Go / unsupported */
      }
    })();
  }, []);
```

Reload the app on the device. If you use a **custom dev client** or **production build**, run a fresh **`npx expo run:android`** (or your usual EAS build) once so the new **`expo-navigation-bar`** plugin is applied in native `AndroidManifest` / styles. **Expo Go** should pick up the runtime calls without rebuilding.

If you later want the nav bar **fully transparent** with content drawing under it (true edge-to-edge), we can switch to `setPositionAsync('absolute')` + a translucent bar and rely only on safe-area padding — say if you want that look.

